"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090932","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-21","<p>Ofgem’s Targeted Charging Review is seeking to ensure all parties connected to the electricity network make a fair contribution to its fixed costs. As was outlined in the ‘After the Trilemma’ speech of 15 November 2018, it is important that we develop an energy system that discourages free riding and ensures a fair distribution of such costs.</p><p> </p><p>Network charging is a matter for Ofgem as the independent regulator, and decisions on its Targeted Charging Review are for it to make. However, Government is working to understand the policy implications of Ofgem’s review proposals across a broad range of interests. The analysis which Ofgem has published as part of its recently closed consultation shows that the proposals could affect investment decisions across a number of technologies, but no final decisions have been taken on timetable or other aspects.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-03-21T12:08:50.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090932/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090932/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-18","Energy: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has made an assessment of the effect of the timetable for Ofgem's Targeted Charging review on (a) investment and (b) innovation in (i) onsite flexible generation and (ii) a future flexible energy system.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","233578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090933","Treasury","false","2019-03-22","<p>There are no current plans to extend the Soft Drinks Industry Levy to other food or drink categories. As set out in Phase 2 of the Childhood Obesity Strategy, HMT will review the Soft Drinks Industry Levy exemption for milk-based drinks in 2020.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-03-22T08:39:19.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090933/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090933/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090933/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-03-18","Sugar: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to extend financial levies on sugar in food and drink to more food and drink categories.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","233504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090934","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-26","<p>There has been no central assessment of the uptake of bariatric surgeries in the United Kingdom compared to other developed countries.</p><p> </p><p>Clinical commissioning groups are responsible for commissioning diabetes services for their local population, including for those patients who require metabolic or bariatric surgery. It is for clinicians to decide when surgery is appropriate based on the need of the patient and in line with the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","233506","2019-03-26T17:20:48.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090934/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090934/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-18","Obesity: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of the reasons for the poor uptake of bariatric surgeries in the UK compared with other developed countries.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","233505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090935","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-26","<p>There has been no central assessment of the uptake of bariatric surgeries in the United Kingdom compared to other developed countries.</p><p> </p><p>Clinical commissioning groups are responsible for commissioning diabetes services for their local population, including for those patients who require metabolic or bariatric surgery. It is for clinicians to decide when surgery is appropriate based on the need of the patient and in line with the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","233505","2019-03-26T17:20:48.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090935/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090935/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-18","Diabetes: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department plans to support an increase in the use of metabolic surgery for people with Type 2 diabetes.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","233506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090936","Treasury","false","2019-03-21","<p>A key component of HMRC’s strategy in tackling the promoters of tax avoidance schemes is to change their behaviour so that they stop this activity altogether. HMRC has a range of powers available to it under the Disclosure of Tax Avoidance Schemes (DOTAS), Promoters of Tax Avoidance Schemes (POTAS), and the Enablers legislation. Charging penalties is not the only sanction available under these regimes. As a result of HMRC’s concerted action, a number of major promoters have now co-operated with HMRC and have either stopped selling schemes or ceased in business altogether. Those who have failed to comply with their obligations under the DOTAS legislation may face penalties. Fewer than 5 penalties have been charged in 2018.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has challenged a number of promoters under the POTAS regime, since it was introduced in 2014, which were complied with as promoters ceased promoting schemes, but none have yet reached the stage of incurring liability to a penalty. The Enablers legislation was introduced in 2017. It imposes a new penalty of 100% of the gross fees, excluding VAT, for any person who enables the use of tax avoidance arrangements that are defeated by HMRC. It is too early for penalties to have been issued.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-03-21T14:54:49.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090936/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090936/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-03-18","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 7 January 2019 to Question 203919 on Tax Avoidance, how many promoters of tax avoidance schemes paid HMRC a penalty in 2018.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","233579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090937","Treasury","false","2019-03-21","<p>Currently HMRC has 326 members of staff who have moved to other Government Departments for an agreed period of time.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-03-21T14:32:13.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090937/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090937/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1090937/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-03-18","Revenue and Customs: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many HMRC staff are currently on secondment to other Government departments.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","233580"
